passages.text: August 28, 2025 05:36 AM GMT

Meituan's large earnings miss in Q2 keeps the debate on competition in the food delivery sector front of mind. We think Meituan's Brazil expansion could be more gradual - a positive for Prosus' iFood- while questions remain on the impact of Meituan's possible entry into the UAE/Kuwait for talabat.

Meituan reported a c.76% EBITDA miss to consensus after competition intensified in Q2. We see an inevitable negative knock- on impact for global food delivery sentiment. Near term implications for Meituan's global expansion plans are unclear, but long term targets remain. We continue to view Prosus' iFood and talabat as strong incumbents/market- leading players.

Meituan - the world's largest food delivery company by GMV - yesterday reported its JunQ results, which come on the back of intensified competition in China since new- entrant JD.com's launch into the market in Q1, alongside existing player Alibaba. It saw Meituan, which holds a c.60- 70% market share in China, report revenues +6% QoQ, but with adj. EBITDA - 77% QoQ, equating to a 76% miss to consensus, while also guiding to a "significant loss" into the SepQ for food delivery and local commerce. The results carry symbolism beyond China for the global food delivery landscape with a possible negative impact to sentiment for the sector with the ability for competition to increase so rapidly within a given quarter. However, an equally pertinent question is why do companies want to spend billions to gain market share on this space? And, with a read- across for Prosus' iFood and talabat, will this result in Meituan decelerating/accelerating its international expansion plans?

Sentiment knock for food delivery: Can competition increase and market shares be impacted in other markets quickly too? The China example could be used to highlight an over- arching concern for all food delivery companies in the way that competition can intensify without notice. JD.com processed 20m orders a day within a few months of launching, gaining c.15% of merchant session share at the peak in April- May on our data below - see Exhibit 1. Our analyst covering Meituan, Gary Yu, recently reduced his long term profit margin to GMV assumption for food delivery GTV from 3%+ to 2.3- 2.4%. Could this happen elsewhere?

We think each region has idiosyncratic traits that are worth considering i.e. not a one- size- fits- all. For example, consumers in the MENA region generally are less price sensitive than other regions due to a lower cost of delivery and higher affluence, among numerous other factors. When asked on the intensification of competition, Meituan's CEO (Wang Xing) noted on the earnings call that "Well, allow me to begin with a very clear message. We are firmly against the involution...the regulators have made it very clear". Regulatory responses are being monitored. In one of Meituan's recently entered geographies, Saudi Arabia, there is draft legislation on ensuring that large food delivery companies charge above the average variable cost per order to prevent aggressive pricing, which could perhaps have positive repercussions for margins in the sector.

What, we think, is perhaps not being asked enough is why companies are choosing to spend billions of dollars to gain a foothold in the food delivery space? Ultimately, food delivery platforms are broadening/have broadened to be more than just food delivery apps, seeking to become 'on- demand' apps i.e. grocery and other retail categories, presenting large TAM opportunities (and potentially far larger than food delivery in the long term). Those more bullish on the sector could suggest that these apps store valuable consumer data. We see value in food delivery companies but a key industry- wide question that is still unanswered is where long term EBITDA margins will settle, which we see as ultimately defining a spread of bull/bear views of the sector.

Is there an impact on Meituan's international expansion plans? Read- across for talabat/Prosus. Meituan first expanded outside of China into Hong Kong in 2023 with a 10 year plan to significantly scale international GMV by 2033 (to c. \(\) 100bn\$ in GMV run- rate). Meituan's CEO noted on the earnings call that "in terms of the expansion phase, so we [are] not in any hurry". In Hong Kong, Meituan compete against Delivery Hero and latterly Deliveroo (which exited the market last year amid competition). Meituan believe they are "number one" in that market now. Meituan expanded into Saudi in late- 2024 and are now in 20 cities by end- July. Last week, Meituan expanded into Qatar (see our report here) and are launching into Brazil to compete against Prosus' iFood which is the dominant market leader there (c. \(80\% +\) share). Meituan noted Brazils a top 5 global market by GMV but that "competition [is] going to be quite fierce" and "we are not in any rush. We want to make sure we do our research", which possibly implies a slower pace of investment in that specific market than we might have expected - positive for iFood. Meituan has been hiring across other GCC markets since April (see our report here) with our attention also focused on the timing of a potential launch by Meituan into the UAE/Kuwait. We current factor an H2 launch into our modelling for the UAE too - see our report here.

We remain Overweight on talabat, believing the risk of competition is overdone by the market. The food delivery/quick grocery markets across MENA are larger, and growing at a faster pace than most estimate. We think the fast market growth should act to help absorb the impact of a new entrant into the market. Even if margins become diluted for talabat, we see upside potential to consensus GMV growth forecasts into 2026 as mitigating some risk to absolute adj. EBITDA progression.

We value talabat on an average of (1) a DCF and (2) FCF yield. (1) Our DCF uses a \(10\%\) WACC, \(3.5\%\) terminal growth, \(12\%\) 10- year revenue CAGR and \(8.9\%\) EBITDA to GMV margin. (2) Our FCF yield is \(3.8\%\) on 2025e, equivalent to Jahez's 2- year average FCF yield which, although it is in line, factors in talabat trading at a \(25\%\) premium on fundamentals, but discounting back \(25\%\) to adjust for Jahez being Saudi listed, i.e. factoring in a \(25\%\) 'Saudi premium'.
